# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: drill
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:drill/2-5d-machining] In machining, **2.5D** refers to a surface which is a projection of a plane into 3rd dimension – although the object is 3-dimensional, there are no overhanging elements possible.
[src:drill/2-5d-machining] Objects of this type are often represented as a contour map that gives the height (*i.e.*, thickness or depth) of the object at each point.
[src:drill/2-5d-machining] 2.5D objects can be machined on a 3-axis milling machine, and do not require any of the features of a higher-axis machine to produce.
[src:drill/2-5d-machining] A typical example involves an XY table that positions for each hole center, where the spindle (Z-axis) then completes a fixed cycle for drilling by plunging and retracting axially.
[src:drill/2-5d-machining] The code for a 2.5D machining is significantly less than 3D contour machining, and the software and hardware requirements are (traditionally) less expensive.
[src:drill/2-5d-machining] **Drilling and tapping centers** are inexpensive, limited-duty machining centers that began as a 2.5-axis market category, although many late-model ones are 3-axis because the software and hardware costs have dropped with advancing technology.
[src:drill/2-5d-machining] A 2.5D image is a simplified three-dimensional (x, y, z) surface representation that contains at most one depth (z) value for every point in the (x, y) plane.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] Abrasive machining works by forcing the abrasive particles, or grains, into the surface of the workpiece so that each particle cuts away a small bit of material.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] Abrasive machining is similar to conventional machining, such as milling or turning, because each of the abrasive particles acts like a miniature cutting tool.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] However, unlike conventional machining the grains are much smaller than a cutting tool, and the geometry and orientation of individual grains are not well defined.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] As a result, abrasive machining is less power efficient and generates more heat.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] The grain size may be different based on the machining.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] For rough grinding, coarse abrasives are used.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] For fine grinding, fine grains (abrasives) are used.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] Abrasive machining processes can be divided into two categories based on how the grains are applied to the workpiece.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] In bonded abrasive processes, the particles are held together within a matrix, and their combined shape determines the geometry of the finished workpiece.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] For example, in grinding the particles are bonded together in a wheel.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] As the grinding wheel is fed into the part, its shape is transferred onto the workpiece.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] In loose abrasive processes, there is no structure connecting the grains.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] They may be applied without lubrication as dry powder, or they may be mixed with a lubricant to form a slurry.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] Since the grains can move independently, they must be forced into the workpiece with another object like a polishing cloth or a lapping plate.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] Common abrasive processes are listed below.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] The most important property of an abrasive is its hardness.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] For abrasive grains to effectively cut, they must be significantly harder than the workpiece material.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] They can be grouped based on their hardness into two categories: conventional abrasives and superabrasives.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] Conventional abrasive materials have been used since the advent of machining.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] They are made of materials that exist naturally on Earth, and they are abundant and cheap.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] Conventional abrasives can suitably machine most materials.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] Superabrasives are much harder than conventional abrasives.
[src:drill/abrasive-machining] Since they are much more expensive, they are used when conventional abrasives will not suffice.
[src:drill/abrasive] An **abrasive** is a material, often a mineral, that is used to shape or finish a workpiece through rubbing which leads to part of the workpiece being worn away by friction.
[src:drill/abrasive] While finishing a material often means polishing it to gain a smooth, reflective surface, the process can also involve roughening as in satin, matte or beaded finishes.
[src:drill/abrasive] In short, the ceramics which are used to cut, grind and polish other softer materials are known as abrasives.
[src:drill/abrasive] Abrasives are extremely commonplace and are used very extensively in a wide variety of industrial, domestic, and technological applications.
[src:drill/abrasive] This gives rise to a large variation in the physical and chemical composition of abrasives as well as the shape of the abrasive.
[src:drill/abrasive] Some common uses for abrasives include grinding, polishing, buffing, honing, cutting, drilling, sharpening, lapping, and sanding (see abrasive machining).
[src:drill/abrasive] Files are not abrasives; they remove material not by scratching or rubbing, but by the cutting action of sharp teeth which have been cut into the surface of the file, very much like those of a saw.
[src:drill/abrasive] However, diamond files are a form of coated abrasive (as they are metal rods coated with diamond powder).
[src:drill/abrasive] Abrasives generally rely upon a difference in hardness between the abrasive and the material being worked upon, the abrasive being the harder of the two substances.
[src:drill/abrasive] However, it is not strictly necessary, as any two solid materials that repeatedly rub against each other will tend to wear each other away; examples include, softer shoe soles wearing away wooden or stone steps over decades or centuries or glaciers abrading stone valleys.
[src:drill/abrasive] However, even softer minerals like calcium carbonate are used as abrasives, such as "polishing agents" in toothpaste.
[src:drill/abrasive] These minerals are either crushed or are already of a sufficiently small size (anywhere from macroscopic grains as large as about 2 mm to microscopic grains about 0.001 mm in diameter) to permit their use as an abrasive.
[src:drill/abrasive] These grains, commonly called grit, have rough edges, often terminating in points which will decrease the surface area in contact and increase the localised contact pressure.
[src:drill/abrasive] The abrasive and the material to be worked are brought into contact while in relative motion to each other.
[src:drill/abrasive] Force applied through the grains causes fragments of the worked material to break away, while simultaneously smoothing the abrasive grain and/or causing the grain to work loose from the rest of the abrasive.
[src:drill/abrasive] Abrasives may be classified as either natural or synthetic.
[src:drill/abrasive] When discussing sharpening stones, natural stones have long been considered superior but advances in material technology are seeing this distinction become less distinct.
[src:drill/abrasive] Many synthetic abrasives are effectively identical to a natural mineral, differing only in that the synthetic mineral has been manufactured rather than mined.
[src:drill/abrasive] Impurities in the natural mineral may make it less effective.
[src:drill/abrasive] Some abrasive minerals (such as zirconia alumina) occur naturally but are sufficiently rare or sufficiently more difficult or costly to obtain such that a synthetic stone is used industrially.
[src:drill/abrasive] Abrasives are shaped for various purposes.
[src:drill/abrasive] Natural abrasives are often sold as dressed stones, usually in the form of a rectangular block.
[src:drill/abrasive] Both natural and synthetic abrasives are commonly available in a wide variety of shapes, often coming as bonded or coated abrasives, including blocks, belts, discs, wheels, sheets, rods and loose grains.
[src:drill/abrasive] A **bonded abrasive** is composed of an abrasive material contained within a matrix, although very fine aluminium oxide abrasive may comprise sintered material.
[src:drill/abrasive] This matrix is called a binder and is often a clay, a resin, a glass or a rubber.
[src:drill/abrasive] This mixture of binder and abrasive is typically shaped into blocks, sticks, or wheels.
[src:drill/abrasive] The most common abrasive used is aluminium oxide.
[src:drill/abrasive] Also common are silicon carbide, tungsten carbide and garnet.
[src:drill/abrasive] Artificial sharpening stones are often a bonded abrasive and are readily available as a two sided block, each side being a different grade of grit.
[src:drill/abrasive] Grinding wheels are cylinders that are rotated at high speed.
[src:drill/abrasive] While once worked with a foot pedal or hand crank, the introduction of electric motors has made it necessary to construct the wheel to withstand greater radial stress to prevent the wheel flying apart as it spins.
[src:drill/abrasive] Similar issues arise with cutting wheels, which are often structurally reinforced with impregnated fibres.
[src:drill/abrasive] High relative speed between abrasive and workpiece often makes necessary the use of a lubricant of some kind.
[src:drill/abrasive] Traditionally, they were called coolants as they were used to prevent frictional heat build up which could damage the workpiece (such as ruining the temper of a blade).
[src:drill/abrasive] Some research suggests that the heat transport property of a lubricant is less important when dealing with metals as the metal will quickly conduct heat from the work surface.
[src:drill/abrasive] More important are their effects upon lessening tensile stresses while increasing some compressive stresses and reducing "thermal and mechanical stresses during chip formation".
[src:drill/abrasive] Various shapes are also used as heads on rotary tools used in precision work, such as scale modelling.
[src:drill/abrasive] Bonded abrasives need to be trued and dressed after they are used.
[src:drill/abrasive] Dressing is the cleaning of the waste material (swarf and loose abrasive) from the surface and exposing fresh grit.
[src:drill/abrasive] Depending upon the abrasive and how it was used, dressing may involve the abrasive being simply placed under running water and brushed with a stiff brush for a soft stone or the abrasive being ground against another abrasive, such as aluminium oxide used to dress a grinding wheel.
[src:drill/abrasive] Truing is restoring the abrasive to its original surface shape.
[src:drill/abrasive] Wheels and stones tend to wear unevenly, leaving the cutting surface no longer flat (said to be "dished out" if it is meant to be a flat stone) or no longer the same diameter across the cutting face.
[src:drill/abrasive] This will lead to uneven abrasion and other difficulties.
[src:drill/abrasive] A *coated abrasive* comprises an abrasive fixed to a backing material such as paper, cloth, rubber, resin, polyester or even metal, many of which are flexible.
[src:drill/abrasive] Sandpaper is a very common coated abrasive.
[src:drill/abrasive] Coated abrasives are most commonly the same minerals as are used for bonded abrasives.
[src:drill/abrasive] A bonding agent (often some sort of adhesive or resin) is applied to the backing to provide a flat surface to which the grit is then subsequently adhered.
[src:drill/abrasive] A woven backing may also use a filler agent (again, often a resin) to provide additional resilience.
[src:drill/abrasive] Coated abrasives may be shaped for use in rotary and orbital sanders, for wrapping around sanding blocks, as handpads, as closed loops for use on belt grinders, as striking surfaces on matchboxes, on diamond plates and diamond steels.
[src:drill/abrasive] Diamond tools, though for cutting, are often abrasive in nature.
[src:drill/abrasive] Sand, glass beads, metal pellets copper slag and dry ice may all be used for a process called sandblasting (or similar, such as the use of glass beads which is "bead blasting").
[src:drill/abrasive] Dry ice will sublimate leaving behind no residual abrasive.
[src:drill/abrasive] Cutting compound used on automotive paint is an example of an abrasive suspended in a liquid, paste or wax, as are some polishing liquids for silverware and optical media.
[src:drill/abrasive] The liquid, paste or wax acts as a binding agent that keeps the abrasive attached to the cloth which is used as a backing to move the abrasive across the work piece.
[src:drill/abrasive] On cars in particular, wax may serve as both a protective agent by preventing exposure of the paint of metal to air and also act as an optical filler to make scratches less noticeable.
[src:drill/abrasive] Toothpaste contains calcium carbonate or silica as a "polishing agent" to remove plaque and other matter from teeth as the hardness of calcium carbonate is less than that of tooth enamel but more than that of the contaminating agent.
[src:drill/abrasive] Very fine rouge powder was commonly used for grinding glass, being somewhat replaced by modern ceramics, and is still used in jewellery making for a highly reflective finish.
[src:drill/abrasive] Cleaning products may also contain abrasives suspended in a paste or cream.
[src:drill/abrasive] They are chosen to be reasonably safe on some linoleum, tile, metal or stone surfaces.
[src:drill/abrasive] However, many laminate surfaces and ceramic topped stoves are easily damaged by these abrasive compounds.
[src:drill/abrasive] Even ceramic/pottery tableware or cookware can damage these surfaces, particularly the bottom of the tableware, which is often unglazed in part or in whole and acts as simply another bonded abrasive.
[src:drill/abrasive] Metal pots and stoves are often scoured with abrasive cleaners, typically in the form of the aforementioned cream or paste or of steel wool and non woven scouring pads which holds fine grits abrasives.
[src:drill/abrasive] Human skin is also subjected to abrasion in the form of exfoliation.
[src:drill/abrasive] Abrasives for this can be much softer and more exotic than for other purposes and may include things like almond and oatmeal.
[src:drill/abrasive] Dermabrasion and microdermabrasion are now rather commonplace cosmetic procedures which use mineral abrasives.
[src:drill/abrasive] Scratched compact discs and DVDs may sometimes be repaired through buffing with a very fine compound, the principle being that a multitude of small scratches will be more optically transparent than a single large scratch.
[src:drill/abrasive] However, this does take some skill and will eventually cause the protective coating of the disc to be entirely eroded (especially if the original scratch is deep), at which time, the data surface will be destroyed if abrasion continues.
[src:drill/abrasive] Silicon carbide powders are commonly used as abrasive materials in various machining processes, including grinding, water-jet cutting, and sandblasting.
[src:drill/abrasive] These powders are effective for fine grinding or rough polishing of semiconductors, ceramics, and ferrous materials.
[src:drill/abrasive] The shape, size and nature of the workpiece and the desired finish will influence the choice of the abrasive used.
[src:drill/abrasive] Also, different shapes of adhesive may make it harder to abrade certain areas of the workpiece.
[src:drill/abrasive] Health hazards can arise from any dust produced (which may be ameliorated through the use of a lubricant) which could lead to silicosis (when the abrasive or workpiece is a silicate) and the choice of any lubricant.
[src:drill/abrasive] Besides water, oils are the most common lubricants.
[src:drill/abrasive] These may present inhalation hazards, contact hazards and, as friction necessarily produces heat, flammable material hazards.
[src:drill/abrasive] An abrasive which is too hard or too coarse can remove too much material or leave undesired scratch marks.
[src:drill/abrasive] Besides being unsightly, scratching can have other, more serious effects.
[src:drill/abrasive] A finer or softer abrasive will tend to leave much finer scratch marks which may even be invisible to the naked eye (a "grainless finish"); a softer abrasive may not even significantly abrade a certain object.
[src:drill/abrasive] A softer or finer abrasive will take longer to cut, as it tends to cut less deeply than a coarser, harder material.
[src:drill/abrasive] Also, the softer abrasive may become less effective more quickly as the abrasive is itself abraded.
[src:drill/abrasive] This allows fine abrasives to be used in the polishing of metal and lenses where the series of increasingly fine scratches tends to take on a much more shiny or reflective appearance or greater transparency.
[src:drill/abrasive] Very fine abrasives may be used to coat the strop for a cut-throat razors, however, the purpose of stropping is not to abrade material but to straighten the burr on an edge.
[src:drill/abrasive] The final stage of sharpening Japanese swords is called polishing and may be a form of superfinishing.
[src:drill/abrasive] Different chemical or structural modifications may be made to alter the cutting properties of the abrasive.
[src:drill/abrasive] Other very important considerations are price and availability.
[src:drill/abrasive] Diamond, for a long time considered the hardest substance in existence, is actually softer than fullerite and even harder aggregated diamond nanorods, both of which have been synthesised in laboratories, but no commercial process has yet been developed.
[src:drill/abrasive] Diamond itself is expensive due to scarcity in nature and the cost of synthesising it.
[src:drill/abrasive] Bauxite is a very common ore which, along with corundum's reasonably high hardness, contributes to corundum's status as a common, inexpensive abrasive.
[src:drill/abrasive] Thought must be given to the desired task about using an appropriately hard abrasive.
[src:drill/abrasive] At one end, using an excessively hard abrasive wastes money by wearing it down when a cheaper, less hard abrasive would suffice.
[src:drill/abrasive] At the other end, if the abrasive substance is too soft, abrasion does not take place in a timely fashion, effectively wasting the abrasive as well as any accruing costs associated with loss of time.
[src:drill/abrasive] Aside from the aforementioned uses of shaping and finishing, abrasives may also be used to prepare surfaces for application of some sort of paint of adhesive.
[src:drill/abrasive] An excessively smooth surface may prevent paint and adhesives from adhering as strongly as an irregular surface could allow.
[src:drill/abrasive] Inflatable tyre repair kits (which, on bicycles particularly, are actually patches for the inner tube rather than the tyre) require use of an abrasive so that the self-vulcanising cement will stick strongly.
[src:drill/abrasive] Inadvertently, people who use knives on glass or metal cutting boards are abrading their knife blades.
[src:drill/abrasive] The pressure at the knife edge can easily create microscopic (or even macroscopic) cuts in the board.
[src:drill/abrasive] This cut is a ready source of abrasive material as well as a channel full of this abrasive through which the edge slides.
[src:drill/abrasive] For this reason, and without regard for the health benefits, wooden boards are much more desirable.
[src:drill/abrasive] A similar occurrence arises with glass-cutters.
[src:drill/abrasive] Glass-cutters have circular blades that are designed to roll not slide.
[src:drill/abrasive] They should never retrace an already effected cut.
[src:drill/abrasive] Undesired abrasion may result from the presence of carbon in internal combustion engines.
[src:drill/abrasive] While smaller particles are readily transported by the lubrication system, larger carbon particles may abrade components with close tolerances.
[src:drill/abrasive] The carbon arises from the excessive heating of engine oil or from incomplete combustion.
[src:drill/abrasive] This soot may contain fullerenes which are noted for their extreme hardness—and small size and limited quantity which would tend to limit their effect.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] In its native habitat it blooms between July and December producing inflorescences that appear in groups of two to eight on an axillary raceme.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] The spherical flower heads have a diameter of 5 to 10 mm (0.20 to 0.39 in) and contain 30 to 50 densely packed pale yellow to nearly white flowers.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] Following flowering, smooth, firmly papery and glabrous seed pods form.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] The curved, twisted or coiled pods have a biconvex shape with a length of 4 to 12 cm (1.6 to 4.7 in) and a width of 5 to 8 mm (0.20 to 0.31 in) and contain longitudinally arranged seeds.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] The species was first formally described by the botanist Robert Brown in 1813 as a part of the William Aiton work *Hortus Kewensis*.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] It was reclassified as *Racosperma melanoxylon* by Leslie Pedley in 1986 then returned to genus *Acacia* in 2006.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] Several other synonyms are known including *Acacia arcuata*, *Mimosa melanoxylon* and *Acacia melanoxylon* var.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] In its native range, *A. melanoxylon* is found down the east coast of Australia from Queensland in the north, into New South Wales, through Victoria and west along the south coast of South Australia.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] It is also found along the east coast of Tasmania.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] It has become naturalised in Western Australia.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] In New South Wales it is widespread from coastal areas and into the Great Dividing Range but is not found further inland.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] It is commonly found at higher altitudes in the Nandewar Range, Liverpool Range and around Orange in the west.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] It is mostly found as a part of wet sclerophyll forest communities or near cooler rainforest communities.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] The range of the tree extends from the Atherton Tableland in northern Queensland and follows the coast to around the Mount Lofty Range in South Australia and can grow in a wide range of podsols, especially in sandy loams.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] Sapwood may range in colour from straw to grey-white with clear demarcation from the heartwood.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] The heartwood is golden to dark brown with chocolate growth rings.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] The timber is generally straight grained but may be wavy or interlocked.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] Quartersawn surfaces may produce an attractive fiddleback figure.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] The wood is lustrous and possesses a fine to medium texture.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] The name of the wood may refer to dark stains on the hands of woodworkers, caused by the high levels of tannin in the timber.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] Australian blackwood seasons easily with some possible cupping when boards are inadequately restrained.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] The timber produces little movement once seasoned.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] The timber is susceptible to attacked by furniture beetles, termites and powder-post beetles (sapwood) due to its physical resistance to effective preservative treatments.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] The timber provides very high chatoyance, with an average value above 26 PZC.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] The species has been introduced to many countries for forestry plantings and as an ornamental tree.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] It now is present in Africa, Asia, Europe, Indian Ocean, the Pacific Ocean, South America and the United States.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] It is a declared noxious weed species in South Africa and is a pest in Portugal's Azores Islands.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] It was also recently listed by the California Invasive Plant Council (Cal-IPC) as an invasive weed that may cause limited impact (Knapp 2003).
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] Its use as a street tree is being phased out in some locales because of the damage it often causes to pavements and underground plumbing.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] In some regions of Tasmania, blackwood is now considered a pest.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] Indigenous Australians use many parts of *A. melanoxylon* for a variety of purposes.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] Seeds are harvested and consumed as a common bush tucker food, and leaves can be used as a soap or fishing poison.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] The bark is either harvested to make string or prepared as a traditional analgesic, while wood is often used to make clap sticks, spear-throwers and shields.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] The live plant is also employed as a fire barrier in rural settings when grown amongst other fire-resistant species.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] Blackwood timber is commercially milled for wood paneling, furniture, joinery and cabinetry, tool handles, boat-building, inlaid boxes and wooden kegs.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] It is often qualitatively compared to walnut hardwood, and its physical properties are well-suited for shaping with steam.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] The bark contains a tannin content of about 20%, and is often engineered to produce decorative wood veneer.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] Plain and figured Australian blackwood is used for musical instruments; in particular, guitars, drums, Hawaiian ukuleles, violin bows and organ pipes.
[src:drill/acacia-melanoxylon] More recently, blackwood has seen an increasing value as a substitute for koa wood.
[src:drill/adze] An **adze** (/ædz/) or **adz** is an ancient and versatile cutting tool similar to an axe but with the cutting edge perpendicular to the handle rather than parallel.
[src:drill/adze] Adzes have been used since the Stone Age.
[src:drill/adze] They are used for smoothing or carving wood in hand woodworking, and as a hoe for agriculture and horticulture.
[src:drill/adze] Two basic forms of an adze are the hand adze (short hoe)—a short-handled tool swung with one hand—and the foot adze (hoe)—a long-handled tool capable of powerful swings using both hands, the cutting edge usually striking at foot or shin level.
[src:drill/adze] A similar tool is called a mattock, which differs by having two blades, one perpendicular to the handle and one parallel.
[src:drill/adze] The adze is depicted in ancient Egyptian art from the Old Kingdom onward.
[src:drill/adze] Originally the adze blades were made of stone, but already in the Predynastic Period copper adzes had all but replaced those made of flint.
[src:drill/adze] Stone blades were fastened to the handle by tying and early bronze blades continued this simple construction.
[src:drill/adze] It was not until the later Bronze Age that the handle passes through an eye at the top of the blade.
[src:drill/adze] Examples of Egyptian adzes can be found in museums and on the Petrie Museum website.
[src:drill/adze] The *ahnetjer* (Manuel de Codage transliteration: *aH-nTr*) depicted as an adze-like instrument, was used in the Opening of the Mouth ceremony, intended to convey power over their senses to statues and mummies.
[src:drill/adze] It was apparently the foreleg of a freshly sacrificed bull or cow with which the mouth was touched.
[src:drill/adze] As Iron Age technology moved south into Africa with migrating ancient Egyptians, they carried their technology with them, including adzes.
[src:drill/adze] To this day, iron adzes are used all over rural Africa for various purposes—from digging pit latrines, and chopping firewood, to tilling crop fields—whether they are of maize (corn), coffee, tea, pyrethrum, beans, millet, yams, or a plethora of other cash and subsistence crops.
[src:drill/adze] Prehistoric Māori adzes from New Zealand were for wood carving, typically made from pounamu sourced from the South Island.
[src:drill/adze] During the Māori Archaic period found on the North Island were commonly made from greywacke from Motutapu Island or basalt from Opito Bay in the Coromandel, similar to adzes constructed on other Pacific Islands.
[src:drill/adze] Early period notched adzes found in Northland were primarily made of argillite quarried from locations around the Marlborough and Nelson regions.
[src:drill/adze] At the same time on Henderson Island, a small coral island in eastern Polynesia lacking any rock other than limestone, native populations may have fashioned giant clamshells into adzes.
[src:drill/adze] American Northwest coast native peoples traditionally used adzes for both functional construction (from bowls to canoes) and art (from masks to totem poles).
[src:drill/adze] Northwest coast adzes take two forms: hafted and D-handle.
[src:drill/adze] The hafted form is similar in form to a European adze with the haft constructed from a natural crooked branch which approximately forms a 60% angle.
[src:drill/adze] The thin end is used as the handle and the thick end is flattened and notched such that an adze iron can be lashed to it.
[src:drill/adze] Modern hafts are sometimes constructed from a sawed blank with a dowel added for strength at the crook.
[src:drill/adze] The second form is the D-handle adze which is basically an adze iron with a directly attached handle.
[src:drill/adze] The D-handle, therefore, provides no mechanical leverage.
[src:drill/adze] Northwest coast adzes are often classified by size and iron shape vs. role.
[src:drill/adze] As with European adzes, iron shapes include straight, gutter and lipped.
[src:drill/adze] Where larger Northwest adzes are similar in size to their European counterparts, the smaller sizes are typically much lighter such that they can be used for the detailed smoothing, shaping and surface texturing required for figure carving.
[src:drill/adze] Final surfacing is sometimes performed with a crooked knife.
[src:drill/adze] Ground stone adzes used to be produced by a variety of people in Western New Guinea (Indonesia), Papua New Guinea and some of the smaller Islands of Melanesia and Micronesia.
[src:drill/adze] The hardstone would have been ground on a riverine rock with the help of water until the desired shape was obtained.
[src:drill/adze] It was then fixed to a natural grown angled wood with resin and plant fibers.
[src:drill/adze] Imported steel axes or machetes have now entirely replaced these tools for decades in even the remotest parts of New Guinea.
[src:drill/adze] Indeed, even before the first foreign missionaries or colonial officials arrived in the New Guinea Highlands, inhabitants had already obtained steel tools through trade with their neighbors.
[src:drill/adze] Stone tools are sometimes manufactured to be sold as curios to tourists.
[src:drill/adze] Modern adzes are made from steel with wooden handles, and enjoy limited use: occasionally in semi-industrial areas, but particularly by "revivalists" such as those at the Colonial Williamsburg cultural center in Virginia, United States.
[src:drill/adze] However, the traditional adze has largely been replaced by the sawmill and the powered plane, at least in industrialised cultures.
[src:drill/adze] It remains in use for some specialist crafts, for example by coopers.
[src:drill/adze] Adzes are also in current use by artists such as Northwest Coast American and Canadian Indigenous sculptors doing totem pole carving, as well as masks and bowls.
[src:drill/adze] "Adzes are used for removing heavy waste, leveling, shaping, or trimming the surfaces of timber" and boards.
[src:drill/adze] Generally, the user stands astride a board or log and swings the adze downwards between his feet, chipping off pieces of wood, moving backwards as they go and leaving a relatively smooth surface behind.
[src:drill/adze] Foot adzes are most commonly known as shipbuilder's or carpenter's adzes.
[src:drill/adze] On the modern, steel adze the cutting edge may be flat for smoothing work to very rounded for hollowing work such as bowls, gutters and canoes.
[src:drill/adze] The shoulders or sides of an adze may be curved called a *lipped adze*, used for notching.
[src:drill/adze] The end away from the cutting edge is called the pole and be of different shapes, generally flat or a *pin pole*.
[src:drill/adze] There are a number of specialist, short-handled adzes used by coopers, wainwrights, and chair makers, and in bowl and trough making.
[src:drill/adze] Many of these have shorter handles for control and more curve in the head to allow better clearance for shorter cuts.
[src:drill/adze] During the communist period of Bulgaria, a new multi-use woodworking adze, called Теслà (*Teslà*), emerged.
[src:drill/adze] It has a sharpened edge perpendicular to the handle, resembling an adze, but it is also used like a carpenter's hammer.
[src:drill/adze] On the back of the head is a textured poll for driving nails, and on the front is a V-shaped hole used for prying, to extract the bent nails.
[src:drill/adze] There is a popular Bulgarian folk song called "На теслата дръжката" (eng: The tesla's handle) about a craftsman and the masculinity of his tool.
[src:drill/agathis] Mature kauri trees have characteristically large trunks, with little or no branching below the crown.
[src:drill/agathis] In contrast, young trees are normally conical in shape, forming a more rounded or irregularly shaped crown as they achieve maturity.
[src:drill/agathis] The bark is smooth and light grey to grey-brown, usually peeling into irregular flakes that become thicker on more mature trees.
[src:drill/agathis] The branch structure is often horizontal or, when larger, ascending.
[src:drill/agathis] The lowest branches often leave annular branch scars when they detach from the lower trunk.
[src:drill/agathis] The juvenile leaves in all species are larger than the adult, more or less acute, varying among the species from ovate to lanceolate.
[src:drill/agathis] Adult leaves are opposite, elliptical to linear, very leathery and quite thick.
[src:drill/agathis] Young leaves are often a coppery-red, contrasting markedly with the usually green or glaucous-green foliage of the previous season.
[src:drill/agathis] The male pollen cones appear usually only on larger trees after seed cones have appeared.
[src:drill/agathis] The female seed cones usually develop on short lateral branchlets, maturing after two years.
[src:drill/agathis] Seeds of some species are attacked by the caterpillars of *Agathiphaga*, some of the most primitive of all living moths.
[src:drill/agathis] Various species of kauri give diverse resins such as kauri gum.
[src:drill/agathis] The timber is generally straight-grained and of fine quality with an exceptional strength-to-weight ratio and rot resistance, making it ideal for yacht hull construction.
[src:drill/agathis] The wood is commonly used in the manufacture of guitars and ukuleles due to its low density and relatively low price of production.
[src:drill/agathis] It is also used for some Go boards (goban).
[src:drill/agathis] The uses of the New Zealand species (*A. australis*) included shipbuilding, house construction, wood panelling, furniture making, mine braces, and railway sleepers.
[src:drill/agathis] Due to the hard resin of the wood, it was the traditionally preferred material used by Māori for wooden weapons, patu aruhe (fernroot beaters) and barkcloth beaters.
[src:drill/agathis] *Agathis*-like leaves are also known from the slightly older Lefipán Formation of the same region, which date to the very end of the Cretaceous.
[src:drill/agathis] Some authors have suggested that *Agathis* is known from earlier in the Cretaceous (Aptian to Cenomanian in North Africa.
[src:drill/agathis] Other fossils of the genus are known from the Eocene of Patagonia, the Late Paleocene-Miocene of southern Australia, and the Oligocene–Miocene of New Zealand.
[src:drill/agathis] The placement of the fossil species *"Agathis" jurassica* from the Late Jurassic of Australia in this genus is doubtful.
[src:drill/air-hammer-fabrication] An **air hammer**, also known as an **air chisel**, is a pneumatic hand tool used to carve in stone, and to break or cut metal objects apart.
[src:drill/air-hammer-fabrication] It is designed to accept different tools depending on the required function.
[src:drill/air-hammer-fabrication] A general tool that can be used to free frozen nuts, insert pins, and align holes.
[src:drill/air-hammer-fabrication] Free-standing air hammers are an adaptation of the hand-held version.
[src:drill/air-hammer-fabrication] An air hammer can stretch or shrink (shape) a variety of metals, from thin aircraft aluminums, all the way down to 10-gauge steel.
[src:drill/air-hammer-fabrication] They are also used for smoothing metal that has already been roughed, shaped or formed.
[src:drill/air-hammer-fabrication] In the 1920s, two pneumatic devices were invented that would permanently change the way metal and stone were hammered.
[src:drill/air-hammer-fabrication] The pneumatic rivet gun was originally developed to set hot rivets on girder bridges and high steel buildings.
[src:drill/air-hammer-fabrication] This tool was later scaled down for sheet metal, as the 1930s saw the advent of monocoque aluminum aircraft.
[src:drill/air-hammer-fabrication] The other new device, hitting at twice or three times the speed of the rivet gun, was the stone carver's hammer – a great blessing for smooth and rapid dressing of granite and marble.
[src:drill/air-hammer-fabrication] Hauschild adapted the original stone carver's hammer into a portable hand-held steel tube frame for the purpose of straightening auto bodies.
[src:drill/air-hammer-fabrication] For the next 25 years his "Ram's Head Body and Fender Machine" improved and increased production for auto body work men all over the U.S.
[src:drill/air-hammer-fabrication] Copying Hauschild's patented design, a pneumatic tool company in Chicago marketed a number of "destined-to-be-classic" pneumatic planishing hammers, both hand-held for auto body work, and also free-standing ones, with a variety of throat depths for industry and manufacturing.
[src:drill/air-hammer-fabrication] By World War II, rivet guns were used widely in U.S. aircraft factories both for riveting aluminum sheets, and for flow forming, the process of working aluminum sheet into and over wooden forms by the application of the pneumatic rivet gun.
[src:drill/air-hammer-fabrication] Post-war industry brought many new applications for the "air hammer" technology.
[src:drill/air-hammer-fabrication] Each of these tools has a different purpose despite nearly identical appearance in many cases.
[src:drill/drill] A **drill** is a tool used for making round holes or driving fasteners.
[src:drill/drill] It is fitted with a drill bit for making holes, or a screwdriver bit for securing fasteners.
[src:drill/drill] Historically, they were powered by hand, and later mains power, but cordless battery-powered drills are proliferating due to increased efficiency and ease of use.
[src:drill/drill] Drills are commonly used in woodworking, metalworking, construction, machine tool fabrication, and utility projects.
[src:drill/drill] Specially designed versions are made for surgery, dentistry, miniatures, and other applications.
[src:drill/drill] Around 35,000 BC, *Homo sapiens* discovered the benefits of the application of rotary tools.
[src:drill/drill] This would have rudimentarily consisted of a pointed rock being spun between the hands to bore a hole through another material.
[src:drill/drill] This led to the hand drill, a smooth stick, that was sometimes attached to flint point, and was rubbed between the palms.
[src:drill/drill] This was used by many ancient civilizations around the world including the Mayans.
[src:drill/drill] The earliest perforated artifacts, such as bone, ivory, shells, and antlers found, are from the Upper Paleolithic era.
[src:drill/drill] Bow drill (strap-drill) are the first machine drills, as they convert a back and forth motion to a rotary motion, and they can be traced back to around 10,000 years ago.
[src:drill/drill] It was discovered that tying a cord around a stick, and then attaching the ends of the string to the ends of a stick (a bow), allowed a user to drill quicker and more efficiently.
[src:drill/drill] Mainly used to create fire, bow-drills were also used in ancient woodwork, stonework, and dentistry.
[src:drill/drill] Archaeologists discovered a Neolithic grave yard in Mehrgarh, Pakistan, dating from the time of the Harappans, around 7,500–9,000 years ago, containing nine adult bodies with a total of eleven teeth that had been drilled.
[src:drill/drill] There are hieroglyphs depicting Egyptian carpenters and bead makers in a tomb at Thebes using bow-drills.
[src:drill/drill] The earliest evidence of these tools being used in Egypt dates back to around 2500 BCE.
[src:drill/drill] The usage of bow-drills was widely spread through Europe, Africa, Asia, and North America, during ancient times and is still used today.
[src:drill/drill] Over the years many slight variations of bow and strap drills have developed for the various uses of either boring through materials or lighting fires.
[src:drill/drill] The core drill was developed in ancient Egypt by 3000 BC.
[src:drill/drill] The pump drill was invented during Roman times.
[src:drill/drill] It consists of a vertical spindle aligned by a piece of horizontal wood and a flywheel to maintain accuracy and momentum.
[src:drill/drill] The hollow-borer tip, first used around the 13th century, consisted of a stick with a tubular shaped piece of metal on the end, such as copper.
[src:drill/drill] This allowed a hole to be drilled while only actually grinding the outer section of it.
[src:drill/drill] This completely separates the inner stone or wood from the rest, allowing the drill to pulverize less material to create a similarly sized hole.
[src:drill/drill] While the pump-drill and the bow-drill were used in Western Civilization to bore smaller holes for a larger part of human history, the auger was used to drill larger holes starting sometime between Roman and Medieval ages.
[src:drill/drill] The auger allowed for more torque for larger holes.
[src:drill/drill] It is uncertain when the brace and bit was invented; however, the earliest picture found so far dates from the 15th century.
[src:drill/drill] It is a type of hand crank drill that consists of two parts as seen in the picture.
[src:drill/drill] The brace, on the upper half, is where the user holds and turns it and on the lower part is the bit.
[src:drill/drill] The bit is interchangeable as bits wear down.
[src:drill/drill] The auger uses a rotating helical screw similar to the Archimedean screw-shaped bit that is common today.
[src:drill/drill] The gimlet is also worth mentioning as it is a scaled down version of an auger.
[src:drill/drill] Archimedes' screw, present in drills to remove perforation dirt from the hole, was invented in Hellenistic Egypt around 300 BCE.
[src:drill/drill] The screw pump is the oldest positive displacement pump.
[src:drill/drill] The first records of a water screw, or screw pump, date back to Hellenistic Egypt before the 3rd century BC.
[src:drill/drill] The Egyptian screw, used to lift water from the Nile, was composed of tubes wound round a cylinder; as the entire unit rotates, water is lifted within the spiral tube to the higher elevation.
[src:drill/drill] A later screw pump design from Egypt had a spiral groove cut on the outside of a solid wooden cylinder and then the cylinder was covered by boards or sheets of metal closely covering the surfaces between the grooves.
[src:drill/drill] In the East, churn drills were invented as early as 221 BC during the Chinese Qin dynasty, capable of reaching a depth of 1500 m.
[src:drill/drill] Churn drills in ancient China were built of wood and labor-intensive, but were able to go through solid rock.
[src:drill/drill] The churn drill appears in Europe during the 12th century.
[src:drill/drill] In 1835 Isaac Singer is reported to have built a steam powered churn drill based on the method the Chinese of a rod tipped with a bit.
[src:drill/drill] Also worth briefly discussing are the early drill presses; they were machine tools that derived from bow-drills but were powered by windmills or water wheels.
[src:drill/drill] Drill presses consisted of the powered drills that could be raised or lowered into a material, allowing for less force by the user.
[src:drill/drill] In 1813 Richard Trevithick designed a steam-driven rotary drill, also the first drill to be powered by steam.
[src:drill/drill] Couch invented the first pneumatic percussion drill.
[src:drill/drill] The next great advancement in drilling technology, the electric motor, led to the invention of the electric drill.
[src:drill/drill] It is credited to mining engineers Arthur James Arnot and William Blanch Brain of Melbourne, Australia who patented the electric drill in 1889.
[src:drill/drill] The first portable handheld drill was created by in 1895 by brothers Wilhelm & Carl Fein of Stuttgart, Germany.
[src:drill/drill] In 1917 the first trigger-switch, pistol-grip portable drill was patented by Black & Decker.
[src:drill/drill] This was the start of the modern drill era.
[src:drill/drill] Over the last century the electric drill has been created in a variety of types and multiple sizes for an assortment of specific uses.
[src:drill/drill] There are many types of drills: some are powered manually, others use electricity (electric drill) or compressed air (*pneumatic drill*) as the motive power, and a minority are driven by an internal combustion engine (for example, earth drilling augers).
[src:drill/drill] Drills with a percussive action (hammer drills) are mostly used in hard materials such as masonry (brick, concrete and stone) or rock.
[src:drill/drill] Drilling rigs are used to bore holes in the earth to obtain water or oil.
[src:drill/drill] Oil wells, water wells, or holes for geothermal heating are created with large drilling rigs.
[src:drill/drill] Some types of hand-held drills are also used to drive screws and other fasteners.
[src:drill/drill] Some small appliances that have no motor of their own may be drill-powered, such as small pumps, grinders, etc.
[src:drill/drill] Some forms of drills have been used since Pre-History, both to make holes in hard objects or as fire drills.
[src:drill/drill] Hand-powered metal drills have been in use for centuries.
[src:drill/drill] Drills powered by electricity (or more rarely, compressed air) are the most common tools in woodworking and machining shops.
[src:drill/drill] Electric drills can be corded (fed from an electric outlet through a power cable) or cordless (fed by rechargeable electric batteries).
[src:drill/drill] The latter have removable battery packs that can be swapped to allow uninterrupted drilling while recharging.
[src:drill/drill] A popular use of hand-held power drills is to set screws into wood, through the use of screwdriver bits.
[src:drill/drill] Drills optimized for this purpose have a clutch to avoid damaging the slots on the screw head.
[src:drill/drill] Most electric hammer drills are rated (input power) at between 600 and 1100 watts.
[src:drill/drill] 1000 watts of input is converted into 500–600 watts of output (rotation of the drill and hammering action).
[src:drill/drill] For much of the 20th century, attachments could commonly be purchased to convert corded electric hand drills into a range of other power tools, such as orbital sanders and power saws, more cheaply than purchasing dedicated versions of those tools.
[src:drill/drill] As the prices of power tools and suitable electric motors have fallen such attachments have become much less common.
[src:drill/drill] Early cordless drills used interchangeable 7.2 V battery packs.
[src:drill/drill] Over the years battery voltages have increased, with 18 V drills being most common, but higher voltages are available, such as 24 V, 28 V, and 36 V.
[src:drill/drill] This allows these tools to produce as much torque as some corded drills.
[src:drill/drill] Common battery types are nickel-cadmium (NiCd) batteries and lithium-ion batteries, with each holding about half the market share.
[src:drill/drill] NiCd batteries have been around longer, so they are less expensive (their main advantage), but have more disadvantages compared to lithium-ion batteries.
[src:drill/drill] NiCd disadvantages are limited life, self-discharging, environment problems upon disposal, and eventually internally short circuiting due to dendrite growth.
[src:drill/drill] Lithium-ion batteries are becoming more common because of their short charging time, longer life, absence of memory effect, and low weight.
[src:drill/drill] Instead of charging a tool for an hour to get 20 minutes of use, 20 minutes of charge can run the tool for an hour in average.
[src:drill/drill] Lithium-ion batteries also hold a charge for a significantly longer time than nickel-cadmium batteries, about two years if not used, vs.
[src:drill/drill] 1 to 4 months for a nickel-cadmium battery.
[src:drill/drill] Also known as impact wrenches, is a form of drill that incorporates a hammer motion along with the rotating motion of a conventional drill.
[src:drill/drill] The hammering aspect of the impact drill occurs when the power of the motor cannot turn the bolt it will begin exerting bursts of force to "hammer" the bolt in the desired direction.
[src:drill/drill] These drills are commonly used to secure long bolts or screws into wood, metal, and concrete, as well as loosening seized or over-tightened bolts.
[src:drill/drill] Impact drills come in two major types, pneumatic and electric, and vary in size depending on application.
[src:drill/drill] Electric impact drills are most often found cordless and are widely used in construction, automobile repair, and fabrication.
[src:drill/drill] These electric drills are preferred over the pneumatic driven because of their maneuverability and ease of use.
[src:drill/drill] Pneumatic impact drills rely on air and have to remain connected to an air source to maintain power.
[src:drill/drill] The chuck on impact drills is different from the conventional handheld power drill.
[src:drill/drill] The chuck acts more as a collet with a hexagonal shape in which the bits and drivers lock into.
[src:drill/drill] Impact drivers can also be used to bore holes like a standard pistol grip drill, but this requires a special bit that will lock into the hexagonal collet.
[src:drill/drill] The design of the impact drills are almost identical to modern pistol grip power drills with only one major difference.
[src:drill/drill] Impact drills have a shorter, skinnier, stubby receiver where the collet is located compared to the larger tapered chuck on a conventional drill.
[src:drill/drill] This allows the user to fit in smaller places that a normal drill would not.
[src:drill/drill] Impact drills are not great in regards to torque and speed control.
[src:drill/drill] Most handheld drills have a variable speed option, whereas most impact drills have a fixed torque and speed.
[src:drill/drill] Impact drills are not designed for precision work due to this lack of adjustability.
[src:drill/drill] The hammer action of a hammer drill is provided by two cam plates that make the chuck rapidly pulse forward and backward as the drill spins on its axis.
[src:drill/drill] This pulsing (hammering) action is measured in Blows Per Minute (BPM) with 10,000 or more BPMs being common.
[src:drill/drill] Because the combined mass of the chuck and bit is comparable to that of the body of the drill, the energy transfer is inefficient and can sometimes make it difficult for larger bits to penetrate harder materials such as poured concrete.
[src:drill/drill] A standard hammer drill accepts 6 mm (1/4 inch) and 13 mm (1/2 inch) drill bits.
[src:drill/drill] The operator experiences considerable vibration, and the cams are generally made from hardened steel to avoid them wearing out quickly.
[src:drill/drill] In practice, drills are restricted to standard masonry bits up to 13 mm (1/2 inch) in diameter.
[src:drill/drill] A typical application for a hammer drill is installing electrical boxes, conduit straps or shelves in concrete.
[src:drill/drill] The rotary hammer (also known as a rotary hammer drill, roto hammer drill or masonry drill).
[src:drill/drill] Standard chucks and parallel-shank carbide-tipped drills have been largely superseded by SDS chucks and matching (spline shank) drills, that have been designed to better withstand and transmit the percussive forces.
[src:drill/drill] These bits are effective at pulverising the masonry and drill into this hard material.
[src:drill/drill] Some styles of this tool are intended for masonry drilling only and the hammer action cannot be disengaged.
[src:drill/drill] Other styles allow the drill to be used without the hammer action for normal drilling, or hammering to be used without rotation for chiselling.
[src:drill/drill] In contrast to the cam-type hammer drill, a rotary/pneumatic hammer drill accelerates only the bit.
[src:drill/drill] This is accomplished through a piston design, rather than a spinning cam.
[src:drill/drill] Rotary hammers have much less vibration and penetrate most building materials.
[src:drill/drill] They can also be used as "drill only" or as "hammer only" which extends their usefulness for tasks such as chipping brick or concrete.
[src:drill/drill] Hole drilling progress is greatly superior to cam-type hammer drills, and these drills are generally used for holes of 19 mm (3/4 inch) or greater in size.
[src:drill/drill] A typical application for a rotary hammer drill is boring large holes for lag bolts in foundations, or installing large lead anchors in concrete for handrails or benches.
[src:drill/drill] A drill press (also known as a pedestal drill, pillar drill, or bench drill) is a style of drill that may be mounted on a stand or bolted to the floor or workbench.
[src:drill/drill] Portable models are made, some including a magnetic base.
[src:drill/drill] Major components include a base, column (or pillar), adjustable table, spindle, chuck, and drill head, usually driven by an electric motor.
[src:drill/drill] The head typically has a set of three handles radiating from a central hub that are turned to move the spindle and chuck vertically.
[src:drill/drill] The distance from the center of the chuck to the closest edge of the column is the throat.
[src:drill/drill] The swing is simply twice the throat, and the swing is how drill presses are classified and sold.
[src:drill/drill] Thus, a tool with 4" throat has an 8" swing (it can drill a hole in the center of an 8" work piece), and is called an 8" drill press.
[src:drill/drill] For most drill presses—especially those meant for woodworking or home use—speed change is achieved by manually moving a belt across a stepped pulley arrangement.
[src:drill/drill] Some drill presses add a third stepped pulley to increase the number of available speeds.
[src:drill/drill] Modern drill presses can, however, use a variable-speed motor in conjunction with the stepped-pulley system.
[src:drill/drill] Medium-duty drill presses such as those used in machine shop (tool room) applications are equipped with a continuously variable transmission.
[src:drill/drill] This mechanism is based on variable-diameter pulleys driving a wide, heavy-duty belt.
[src:drill/drill] This gives a wide speed range as well as the ability to change speed while the machine is running.
[src:drill/drill] Heavy-duty drill presses used for metalworking are usually of the gear-head type described below.
[src:drill/drill] Drill presses are often used for miscellaneous workshop tasks other than drilling holes.
[src:drill/drill] This includes sanding, honing, and polishing.
[src:drill/drill] These tasks can be performed by mounting sanding drums, honing wheels and various other rotating accessories in the chuck.
[src:drill/drill] This can be unsafe in some cases, as the chuck arbor, which may be retained in the spindle solely by the friction of a taper fit, may dislodge during operation if the side loads are too high.
[src:drill/drill] A geared head drill press transmits power from the motor to the spindle through spur gearing inside the machine's head, eliminating a flexible drive belt.
[src:drill/drill] This assures a positive drive at all times and minimizes maintenance.
[src:drill/drill] Gear head drills are intended for metalworking applications where the drilling forces are higher and the desired speed (RPM) is lower than that used for woodworking.
[src:drill/drill] Levers attached to one side of the head are used to select different gear ratios to change the spindle speed, usually in conjunction with a two- or three-speed motor (this varies with the material).
[src:drill/drill] Most machines of this type are designed to be operated on three-phase electric power and are generally of more rugged construction than equivalently sized belt-driven units.
[src:drill/drill] Virtually all examples have geared racks for adjusting the table and head position on the column.
[src:drill/drill] Geared head drill presses are commonly found in tool rooms and other commercial environments where a heavy duty machine capable of production drilling and quick setup changes is required.
[src:drill/drill] In most cases, the spindle is machined to accept Morse taper tooling for greater flexibility.
[src:drill/drill] Larger geared head drill presses are frequently fitted with power feed on the quill mechanism, with an arrangement to disengage the feed when a certain drill depth has been achieved or in the event of excessive travel.
[src:drill/drill] Some gear-head drill presses have the ability to perform tapping operations without the need for an external tapping attachment.
[src:drill/drill] This feature is commonplace on larger gear head drill presses.
[src:drill/drill] A clutch mechanism drives the tap into the part under power and then backs it out of the threaded hole once the proper depth is reached.
[src:drill/drill] Coolant systems are also common on these machines to prolong tool life under production conditions.
[src:drill/drill] A radial arm drill press is a large geared-head drill press in which the head can be moved along an arm that radiates from the machine's column.
[src:drill/drill] As it is possible to swing the arm relative to the machine's base, a radial arm drill press is able to operate over a large area without having to reposition the workpiece.
[src:drill/drill] This feature saves considerable time because it is much faster to reposition the machine's head than it is to unclamp, move, and then re-clamp the workpiece to the table.
[src:drill/drill] The size of work that can be handled may be considerable, as the arm can swing out of the way of the table, allowing an overhead crane or derrick to place a bulky workpiece on the table or base.
[src:drill/drill] A vise may be used with a radial arm drill press, but more often the workpiece is secured directly to the table or base, or is held in a fixture.
[src:drill/drill] Power spindle feed is nearly universal with these machines and coolant systems are common.
[src:drill/drill] Larger-size machines often have power feed motors for elevating or moving the arm.
[src:drill/drill] The biggest radial arm drill presses are able to drill holes as large as four inches or 100 mm diameter in solid steel or cast iron.
[src:drill/drill] Radial arm drill presses are specified by the diameter of the column and the length of the arm.
[src:drill/drill] The length of the arm is usually the same as the maximum throat distance.
[src:drill/drill] The radial arm drill press pictured to the right has a 9-inch diameter and a 3-foot-long arm.
[src:drill/drill] The maximum throat distance of this machine would be approximately 36 inches, giving a maximum swing of 72 inches (6 feet or 1.8 m).
[src:drill/drill] A **magnetic drill** is a portable machine for drilling holes in large and heavy workpieces which are difficult to move or bring to a stationary conventional drilling machine.
[src:drill/drill] It has a magnetic base and drills holes with the help of cutting tools like annular cutters (broach cutters) or with twist drill bits.
[src:drill/drill] There are various types depending on their operations and specializations, like magnetic drilling / tapping machines, cordless, pneumatic, compact horizontal, automatic feed, cross table base etc.
[src:drill/drill] Mill drills are a lighter alternative to a milling machine.
[src:drill/drill] They combine a drill press (belt driven) with the X/Y coordinate abilities of the milling machine's table and a locking collet that ensures that the cutting tool will not fall from the spindle when lateral forces are experienced against the bit.
[src:drill/drill] Although they are light in construction, they have the advantages of being space-saving and versatile as well as inexpensive, being suitable for light machining that may otherwise not be affordable.
[src:drill/drill] Drills are used in surgery to remove or create holes in bone; specialties that use them include dentistry, orthopedic surgery and neurosurgery.
[src:drill/drill] The development of surgical drill technology has followed that of industrial drilling, including transitions to the use of lasers, endoscopy, use of advanced imaging technologies to guide drilling, and robotic drills.
[src:drill/drill] Drills are often used simply as motors to drive a variety of applications, in much the same way that tractors with generic PTOs are used to power ploughs, mowers, trailers, etc.
[src:drill/drill] Drilling capacity indicates the maximum diameter a given power drill or drill press can produce in a certain material.
[src:drill/drill] It is essentially a proxy for the continuous torque the machine is capable of producing.
[src:drill/drill] Typically a given drill will have its capacity specified for different materials, i.e., 10 mm for steel, 25 mm for wood, etc.
